INSERT INTO training_lessons (id, module_id, title, content, estimated_minutes, sort_order, created_at)
SELECT 
  gen_random_uuid(),
  id,
  'Identifying Suspicious Transactions and Red Flags',
  E'# Recognizing Money Laundering Indicators\n\n## Understanding Money Laundering Stages\n\nMoney laundering typically occurs in three stages:\n\n### 1. Placement\nIntroducing illegal funds into the financial system.\n\n**Casino Examples:**\n- Purchasing chips with large amounts of cash\n- Multiple transactions just below reporting thresholds\n- Buying chips at multiple cashiers simultaneously\n\n### 2. Layering  \nCreating complex transaction trails to obscure the money''s origin.\n\n**Casino Examples:**\n- Exchanging chips repeatedly between different denominations\n- Minimal gaming followed by chip redemption\n- Transferring chips to third parties\n- Using multiple player accounts\n\n### 3. Integration\nReintroducing the "cleaned" money into the legitimate economy.\n\n**Casino Examples:**\n- Requesting casino cheques instead of cash\n- Winning declarations for small amounts played\n- Using casino credit facilities improperly\n\n## Red Flags: Suspicious Customer Behaviors\n\n### Transaction-Based Indicators\n\n**Large Cash Transactions**\n- Cash deposits or chip purchases exceeding R25,000\n- Reluctance to provide identification for large transactions\n- Use of multiple smaller transactions to avoid limits (structuring)\n- Large transactions inconsistent with known customer profile\n\n**Example Scenario**: A customer approaches three different cashiers within 30 minutes, purchasing R24,000 in chips at each window. Total: R72,000. This is clear structuring to avoid the R25,000 single-transaction reporting threshold.\n\n**Minimal Gaming Activity**\n- Purchasing large amounts of chips but playing little or not at all\n- Brief gaming session followed by immediate redemption\n- Betting patterns that seem designed to lose minimally\n- "Playing" without appearing interested in the games\n\n**Example Scenario**: Customer buys R100,000 in chips, plays roulette for 15 minutes with minimum R100 bets, loses R2,500, then cashes out R97,500 and requests a cheque. The customer has essentially exchanged cash for a casino cheque with minimal gaming.\n\n**Chip Transactions**\n- Attempting to exchange chips without having played\n- Requesting chip exchanges for large amounts\n- Chips from other casinos presented for redemption\n- Chips that appear old or do not match current casino sets\n\n### Behavioral Indicators\n\n**Avoidance Behaviors**\n- Reluctance to provide identification or personal information\n- Providing false, inconsistent, or suspicious identification\n- Nervousness when questioned about transactions\n- Leaving when approached by staff or security\n- Avoiding areas with surveillance cameras\n\n**Unusual Patterns**\n- Only visiting the casino for brief periods\n- No interest in complimentary services or amenities\n- Multiple visits in a single day for chip transactions\n- Accompanied by others who appear to be directing activities\n\n**Profile Inconsistencies**\n- Transactions inconsistent with stated occupation or income\n- Young customers conducting large transactions\n- Claims of first visit but demonstrates detailed knowledge\n- Address provided is false or cannot be verified\n\n## Geographic Risk Factors\n\n### High-Risk Jurisdictions\n\nCustomers from certain countries pose elevated money laundering risks:\n\n**Financial Action Task Force (FATF) Listed Countries**\n- Countries with strategic AML deficiencies\n- Non-cooperative jurisdictions\n- Check current FATF lists (updated regularly)\n\n**Common High-Risk Indicators in South Africa:**\n- Customers claiming residence in known tax havens\n- Recent arrival from high-risk jurisdiction\n- Passport from country with weak financial controls\n- Multiple citizenship documents from risk countries\n\n## Industry-Specific Red Flags\n\n### VIP Room Activities\n- Private gaming rooms used for brief periods\n- Large chip transactions with minimal play\n- Multiple persons using same VIP facility\n- Chips transferred between VIP customers\n\n### Junket Operations\n- Junket participants not actually gaming\n- Chip redemptions not matching play patterns\n- Unknown individuals joining junket groups\n\n### Cash Cage Observations\n- Customers providing identification reluctantly\n- Multiple individuals conducting similar transactions\n- Customers claiming to represent others\n- Structured deposits across multiple accounts\n\n## The Importance of Context\n\nNo single indicator confirms money laundering. You must consider:\n\n1. **Pattern Recognition**: Are multiple red flags present?\n2. **Customer History**: Is this behavior unusual for this customer?\n3. **Transaction Context**: Does the transaction make sense?\n4. **Combined Factors**: What is the overall picture?\n\n## Practical Exercise\n\n### Scenario Analysis\n\nConsider this situation:\n\n*Three men in their early 20s arrive together. Each approaches a different cashier and purchases R24,000 in chips with cash. They meet at a slot machine, play for about 10 minutes with minimal wagers, then return to separate cashiers to redeem their chips, requesting casino cheques. Each provides a driver''s license showing the same residential address.*\n\n**Red Flags Present:**\n1. Structured transactions (3 x R24,000 to avoid R25,000 threshold)\n2. Coordinated behavior\n3. Minimal gaming activity\n4. Same address (possible straw man scheme)\n5. Young age inconsistent with R72,000 cash transaction\n6. Immediate redemption to cheques\n\n**Appropriate Action:** This situation should be reported to your supervisor immediately. Multiple serious indicators suggest money laundering activity.\n\n## Documentation Requirements\n\nWhen you observe suspicious activities:\n\n1. **Note the Facts**: Record what you observed, not conclusions\n2. **Be Specific**: Include times, amounts, denominations\n3. **Identify Individuals**: Physical descriptions, clothing, identification\n4. **Preserve Evidence**: Keep transaction records, CCTV timestamps\n5. **Report Promptly**: Don''t wait - report immediately\n\n## Remember: When in Doubt, Report\n\nIt is better to report a transaction that turns out to be legitimate than to fail to report actual money laundering. You will not face consequences for good-faith reports of suspicious activities.\n\n**Next Lesson**: Customer Due Diligence and Reporting Procedures',
  15,
  2,
  NOW()
FROM training_modules
WHERE title = 'AML Basics for Casino Staff';

